event: response.output_text.done
data: {"type":"response.output_text.done","content_index":0,"item_id":"msg_03e6087385ea59fe006a25ee83b0d48199816e0ab4fabf7510","logprobs":[],"output_index":1,"sequence_number":437,"text":"OpenSSL traces its origins to the earlier SSLeay project, an open-source implementation of the Secure Sockets Layer protocol created in the 1990s by Eric A. Young and Tim J. Hudson. SSLeay became widely used because it provided a freely available cryptographic toolkit at a time when secure internet communication was becoming increasingly important. After Young and Hudson moved on to other work, the SSLeay codebase was effectively succeeded by OpenSSL, whose first public release appeared in 1998. The project aimed to provide a robust, open-source implementation of SSL and, later, TLS, along with a general-purpose cryptography library and command-line tools for certificate management, encryption, hashing, and testing.\n\nThroughout the 2000s, OpenSSL became a foundational component of internet infrastructure. It was integrated into web servers such as Apache and Nginx, mail servers, VPN software, operating systems, embedded devices, and countless applications requiring encrypted communication. Its broad adoption was partly due to its permissive licensing, portability, and support for a wide range of cryptographic algorithms and protocols. However, OpenSSL also developed a reputation for being complex and difficult to maintain. Much of the code had accumulated over many years, and the project historically operated with a small team and limited funding despite its enormous importance to global network security.\n\nThe most famous turning point in OpenSSL’s history came in 2014 with the disclosure of the Heartbleed vulnerability, a serious flaw in OpenSSL’s implementation of the TLS heartbeat extension. Heartbleed allowed attackers to read portions of memory from affected servers, potentially exposing private keys, passwords, and other sensitive data. The incident drew worldwide attention to the underfunded state of critical open-source security projects and led to major reforms. Funding initiatives such as the Core Infrastructure Initiative were launched, and OpenSSL itself underwent code audits, cleanup efforts, and governance changes. In the years since, the project has continued to evolve, adding support for newer TLS standards such as TLS 1.3, deprecating older insecure protocols and algorithms, and remaining one of the most important cryptographic libraries in modern computing."}

